fields.new_content:
Software Engineer/ Automation Test Engineer

• Developed a full-stack web application that runs MS tests in isolation in Docker to speed up the execution time of nightly runs by 2/3.

• Compiled a documentation for web application and a 35-page legacy documentation for new Co-op students so that shorten the training phase.

• Automated, workflows, maintenance and deployment procedures using Microsoft TFS.

• Created process to build and run nightly tests with localized builds and reduced building time.

• Upgraded, maintenance, configure and take snapshot of servers and VMs by using vShpere.

• Implemented scripts can automatically download, upload,  and check for duplication documents in CouchBase.

• Joined Machine Learning Group to identify whether patient has pneumonia.

• Experienced Quality Assurance Analyst with a demonstrated history of working in the public safety industry.

• Skilled in Performance, Load, Stress Testing, UI, Compatibility and regression Testing .

• Collaborated in group work, worked with product manager make sure all the requirements are tested.

• Explored defect life cycle, identified bugs reported a related issue and documented steps to reproduce bugs on Jira.

C++, googletest

• Created a buffer pool for holding pinned pages generated from hard-disk, developed a buffer pool manager which can manage which page store data or which page need to be flushed.

• Implemented a index manger using Skip-List to speed up indexing.

• Developed a lock manager which integrated share/exclusive lock to prevent potential multithreading issue. e.g. Different transactions read/write same record in database.

• Wrote a wound and wait technique to avoid deadlock by using condition_variable.

• Used google-test to do bench-marking for each functionalities I implemented.

Node.js, Angular, sequlize

• Designed relational database structure, set up and maintenance database in PostgreSQL.

• Created migration files and seeder files for testing purposes.

• Implemented APIs which allow other team members update/modify/change tuples in database.

• Engaged the Google Cloud Service such as Google Cloud Storage for storing images uploaded by users, and deploying our website to Google cloud platform.

• Developed user profile page include showing following/follower modal and follow button, cat page, add cat modal window, recommend user panel and infinite scroll in main page, user page and cat page, and hot fix during

Python3.x

• Implemented a sudoku solver using backtracking algorithm.

• Developed a program can take an image of Sudoku as input and extract digits on the image and convert them to matrix, then put in to grid.

• Created a simple UI using Tkinter. Users are allowed to type in the corresponding numbers in an Sudoku question, and hit solve button to generate a solution for the Sudoku question.

• Bottleneck:

  1. Different resolution may vary the result.
  2. For different fonts, the accuracy changes. So far, the best score I have hit is 86% percent for a certain font.
  3. After getting binary clipped images, I need to feed them to the model I trained and convert back at the end, which has a high time complexity.

Hackathon background:

The event is coordinated by the BMIA cluster, funded and supported by the Vice President of Research and Innovation’s Office as well as the Institute of Computing, Information and Cognitive Systems (ICICS).

This event brought together students interested in exploring computer science in the context of biomedical applications is an increasingly hot topic. Wewere given two challenges using different data sets and encouraged to form small teams (or work alone) to generate a solution on our own computers.

What we did:

Twitter sentiment classifier

python3.x, sklearn, SVM

The task is to build a model that will determine the tone (neutral, positive, negative) of the text. To do this, you will need to train the model on the existing data (train.csv). The resulting model will have to determine the class (neutral, positive, negative) of new texts (test data that were not used to build the model) with maximum accuracy.

Team Swat Team, first place winners of the Twitter challenge

Hackathon background:

Mountain Madness is the annual hackathon organized by the SFU Computing Science Student Society. 

Some examples and inspiration:

  1. A magic eight-ball program that, given a query, simulates a large network and runs a distributed consensus algorithm to arrive at its answer
  2. The echo command line tool, but each character is printed by a new Docker container
  3. Shazoom—an iPhone app that builds an Android virtual machine, installs Shazam on it, and then runs Shazam on the virtual machine

What we did:

elgooG: Mountain Madness Hackathon 2019 Project

node.js, selenium

The app is composed of a web front-end and two nodejs back-ends.

  1. A user types a keyword on the search bar in a browser (front-end).
  2. The keyword sends back to Back-end#1(BE1), then it opens up a browser with selenium and searches the same keyword on google.
  3. BE1 then sends a post request to Back-end#2(BE2) and tell BE2 to take a picture of BE1's screen (yes, for this to work, we need two laptops running the two BEs and placed them face to face).
  4. BE2 sends the picture back to BE1, which processes the picture taken in https://www.onlineocr.net/ and records the result.
  5. BE1 extracts the text from the picture, and sends both the picture and text to the font-end.
  6. Users can enjoy the super helpful elgooG result.
